<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Defined Earnings Per Share (Annual Cash Incentive Program)</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Adjusted Earnings Per Share Growth (Performance Share Units)</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Adjusted EPS is defined as diluted EPS
attributable to Mondel&#275;z International from continuing operations excluding the impacts of:</P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Spin-Off Costs;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;the 2012-2014 Restructuring Program;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;the 2014-2018 Restructuring Program;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;the Integration Program and other acquisition
integration costs;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;the Venezuela deconsolidation loss;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;the remeasurement of net monetary assets in
Venezuela;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;the net benefit from the Cadbury acquisition-related
indemnification resolution;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;losses on debt extinguishment and related
expenses;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;the residual tax benefit impact from the resolution
of the Starbucks arbitration;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;hedging gains/losses and incremental costs
associated with the coffee transactions;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;impairment charges related to goodwill and intangible assets;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;gains or losses on interest swaps no longer
designated as accounting cash flow hedges due to changed financing and hedging plans;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;gains or losses from divestitures<SUP
STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</SUP> or acquisitions;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;gain on the coffee business transactions<SUP
STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(2)</SUP>;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;divestiture-related costs;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;acquisition-related costs; and</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;net earnings from divestitures<SUP
STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</SUP>;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>And including:</I></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;an adjustment to our equity method investment
earnings for our proportionate share of unusual or infrequent items, such as acquisition and divestiture-related costs and restructuring program costs, recorded by our JDE equity method investee.</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Defined Earnings Per Share</I>: Defined as
Adjusted EPS calculated at currency exchange rates utilized in our internal financial planning for 2015. In addition, due to the deconsolidation of Venezuela at the end of 2015, Venezuela operations were excluded from the calculation of targets and
results<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(3)</SUP>.</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Adjusted Earnings Per Share
Growth: </I>Actual Adjusted EPS results as calculated based on the definition of Adjusted EPS for each year of the three-year performance cycle. Each year&#146;s growth is then measured based upon the prior year&#146;s currency exchange
rates.</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">Indicator of overall business trends and performance, based on what business leaders can control.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<TD VALIGN="top" COLSPAN="3" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Free Cash Flow (Net Cash Provided By Operating Activities less

associated with acquisition);</P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;51 </FONT></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(2)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">In connection with the global coffee business transactions that closed on July&nbsp;2, 2015, because we exchanged our coffee interests for similarly-sized coffee interests in Jacobs Douwe Egberts (&#147;JDE&#148;)
(which, following the July&nbsp;2, 2015 closing, was 43.5% of our historical and D.E. Master Blenders 1753 B.V.&#146;s combined global coffee businesses), we have deconsolidated and not included our historical global coffee business results within
divestitures in our non-GAAP financial measures. We continue to have an ongoing interest in the coffee business. Beginning in the third quarter of 2015, we have included the after-tax earnings of JDE and of our historical coffee business results
within continuing results of operations. For Adjusted EPS, we have included these earnings in equity method investment earnings and have deconsolidated our historical coffee business results from Organic Net Revenue and Adjusted Operating Income to
facilitate comparisons of past and future operating results. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(3)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Effective as of the close of the 2015 fiscal year, we concluded that we no longer met the accounting criteria for consolidation of our Venezuela subsidiaries due to a loss of control over our Venezuelan operations and
an other-than temporary lack of currency exchangeability. As of the close of the 2015 fiscal year, we deconsolidated and changed to the cost method of accounting for our Venezuelan operations. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Deferred Compensation </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In 2015, our NEOs were eligible to participate in the
Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Executive Deferred Compensation Plan (&#147;MEDCP&#148;), a voluntary non-qualified deferred compensation plan. The program is similar to those provided to executive officers at many of the companies in our Compensation
Survey Group and is provided for recruitment purposes and to assist executives in managing their future cash flow. The deferred compensation plan provides an opportunity for executives to defer, on a pre-tax basis, up to 50% of their salary and up
to 100% of their award under the Annual Cash Incentive Program. Executives may invest deferred amounts in one or more notional investment options. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Executive
Perquisites </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We offer our NEOs executive physicals as well as car and financial allowances. Additionally, based on the findings of an independent, third-party
security study, we require Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld to use the corporate aircraft for business and personal travel. This also allows Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld to be more productive and efficient when she travels, particularly considering we do business in
approximately 165 countries. NEOs are solely responsible for all taxes on all perquisites. We do not provide tax gross ups. We offer limited perquisites similar to those offered by companies in our Compensation Survey Group and do so at comparable
costs. The Compensation Committee believes these limited perquisites are important for retention and recruitment. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In 2015, the Compensation Committee approved
reimbursement of a $45,000 filing fee incurred by Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld in connection with a required filing under the Hart-Scott-Rodino Antitrust Improvements Act (&#147;HSR&#148;). The filing was required because the dollar value of shares held by
Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld exceeded thresholds established under HSR, due to share price appreciation and vesting in equity awards. The Compensation Committee considered it appropriate to reimburse Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld because the expense resulted from the
operation of our equity compensation program and Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is required to hold significant equity under our stock ownership and holding requirements. Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is responsible for income taxes on the reimbursement and, in line with
our policy described above, we did not provide any tax gross-up. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The footnotes to the Summary Compensation Table under &#147;Executive Compensation Tables&#148;
list our NEOs&#146; 2015 perquisites. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Retirement and Separation Benefits </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As described below, we offer our NEOs retirement and separation benefits. We do not have employment agreements with any of our NEOs. They are all &#147;at will&#148;
employees, including Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Retirement Benefits </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Generally,
our NEOs are eligible for broad-based U.S. employee benefit plans, including two tax-qualified plans&nbsp;&#150;&nbsp;the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Retirement Plan (&#147;Retirement Plan&#148;) and the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Thrift Plan
(&#147;Thrift Plan&#148;). U.S. employees hired after 2008 are not eligible to participate in the Retirement Plan or the defined benefit portion of the Supplemental Plan (as defined below). In addition, accruals under the Retirement Plan and the
defined benefit portion of the Supplemental Plan will cease after 2019. U.S. employees hired after 2008 who are not eligible to participate in the Retirement Plan are eligible to receive an enhanced employer contribution under the Thrift Plan and
the defined contribution portion of the Supplemental Plan. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;52 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We also provide an unfunded non-qualified plan, the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan (&#147;Supplemental
Plan&#148;), for eligible U.S. employees. The Supplemental Plan provides benefits that are not provided under the Retirement Plan or Thrift Plan due to an employee&#146;s compensation exceeding the tax-qualified plan compensation limit under Code
Section&nbsp;401(a)(17), an employee&#146;s election to defer compensation under either the MEDCP or the Supplemental Plan, or a Retirement Plan participant&#146;s benefit exceeding the limits under Section&nbsp;415 of the Code. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We provide Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld with a non-qualified, enhanced pension benefit that credits her pension service for the period of time (2004-2006) that she was not
employed by the Company. We provide this enhanced pension benefit to Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld because, when she rejoined the Company, she forfeited her right to a pension benefit at her previous employer. This benefit was part of a broader incentive
program to help encourage her to return to the Company and become our CEO. The 2015 Pension Benefits table and the accompanying narrative to the table under &#147;Executive Compensation Tables&#148; provide additional details about this benefit.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Compensation Committee believes the Retirement Plan, Thrift Plan and non-qualified Supplemental Plan are integral parts of our overall executive compensation
program. The Compensation Committee believes our NEOs should receive the same defined benefit accruals, be able to defer the same percentage of their compensation and receive the same corresponding notional employer contributions as all other
employees, without regard to the Code&#146;s compensation limit applicable to tax-qualified plans or whether the NEO has elected to defer compensation. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Change
in Control Severance Plan </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We maintain a Change in Control Severance Plan (the &#147;CIC Plan&#148;) for senior executive officers. The CIC Plan is consistent
with similar plans maintained by companies in our Compensation Survey Group, including eligibility and severance benefit levels. We structure separation payments to help assure that key executives, including our NEOs, would be available to assist in
the successful transition following a change in control and provide a competitive level of severance protection if the executive is involuntarily terminated without cause or resigns for good reason within two years following a change in control
(&#147;double trigger&#148;). In the event that a payment under the CIC Plan or otherwise triggers an excise tax under Code Section&nbsp;4999, the payment will be the greater of the full benefit or a reduced benefit that does not trigger the excise
tax as determined on an after-tax basis for each. We do not provide any tax gross ups for taxes payable on change in control benefits. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In 2015, we decreased the
CEO&#146;s severance multiple from 3 times base salary to 2.99 times base salary. We further describe the severance arrangements and other benefits provided under the CIC Plan (as well as the equity treatment upon certain separations in the event of
a change in control) under &#147;Executive Compensation Tables &#150; Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Non-Change in Control
Severance Agreements </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Although we generally do not have individual severance or employment agreements with any of our NEOs, we would typically provide separation
benefits as consideration for entering into an agreement protecting our interests. The severance payments and other benefits provided to a typical NEO are described under &#147;Executive Compensation Tables &#150; Potential Payments upon Termination
or Change in Control.&#148; </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;53 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2015 Annual Cash Incentive Program Award </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Cofer&#146;s 2015 individual performance rating primarily related to strong performance for the Asia Pacific and Eastern Europe, Middle East and Africa regions
through delivery of solid financial results relative to target despite economic and political instability in certain areas. Mr.&nbsp;Cofer also led the successful implementation of restructuring changes across our Asia Pacific and Eastern Europe,
Middle East and Africa regions. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2015 Equity Grants (Non-Qualified Stock Options and Performance Share Units and Deferred Stock Units) </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Cofer&#146;s annual equity grant reflects his individual performance and external market positioning. Mr.&nbsp;Cofer also received a retention grant as
described under &#147;&#150; Description of Individual Executive Compensation Program Elements &#150; Equity Program &#150; 2015 Retention Equity Grants&#148;. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>International Assignment Payments </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As a U.S. expatriate, Mr.&nbsp;Cofer
received payments in 2015 in conjunction with his international assignment based in Singapore. These payments to Mr.&nbsp;Cofer were similar to the types of payments generally made to other employees who accept an international assignment with the
Company under our International Assignment Policy. Our International Assignment Policy is designed to facilitate relocation of employees to positions in other countries by covering expenses over and above those that the employees would have incurred
had they remained in their home countries. Such payments include housing expenses, cost of living adjustment, education and travel expenses. Similarly, our International Assignment Policy covers the additional taxes employees incur due solely to
their international assignments. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mr.&nbsp;Marques </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Commencement of
Employment </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">On March&nbsp;9, 2015, Mr.&nbsp;Marques commenced employment as the Executive Vice President and President, North America. To offset the loss of
certain long-term incentives and retirement benefits from his previous employer, incent him to join the Company, and immediately align his compensation with our key critical performance measures and the interests of shareholders, the Compensation
Committee approved a one-time cash payment of $1,100,000, subject to full repayment if his employment with us terminates before March&nbsp;9, 2017 (except for an involuntary termination without cause or termination due to death or disability), and a
one-time equity grant of 130,900 shares of restricted stock and 654,460 NQSOs. The performance-based portion of the equity grant, approximately half of the total grant value, only rewards Mr.&nbsp;Marques if there is an increase in our share price
(NQSOs). The shares of restricted stock ratably vest 30%, 30% and 40% annually on the anniversary of Mr.&nbsp;Marques&#146; date of hire and are subject to the same terms and conditions as the restricted stock grants made to other employees
generally on February&nbsp;18, 2015 with the exception that the shares of restricted stock vest upon an involuntary termination without cause. The NQSOs ratably vest 30%, 30% and 40% annually on the anniversary of Mr.&nbsp;Marques&#146; date of hire
and are generally subject to the same terms as the grants made to the NEOs on February&nbsp;18, 2015 with the exception that any outstanding stock options will vest with a one-year post-termination exercise period upon an involuntary termination
without cause. Due to the timing of his hire, Mr.&nbsp;Marques received a 2015 annual equity grant of 76,140 NQSOs and 45,690 performance share units on March&nbsp;9, 2015. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Target Total Direct Compensation </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Marques&#146; target compensation
levels are above the median of our Compensation Survey Group primarily because of his significant prior operating experience in the consumer products industry. Mr.&nbsp;Marques&#146; annual base salary of $875,000, his target annual incentive of 80%
of his base salary and his 2015 annual equity grant generally reflect internal and external peer positioning. Mr.&nbsp;Marques&#146; 2015 individual performance rating reflects solid financial performance for our North American region in a
challenging operating environment. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;56 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc119433_37"></A>Policy Authorizing Recoupment of Executive Incentive Compensation in the
</B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Event of Certain Restatements </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Board or an
appropriate committee of the Board may determine that, as a result of a restatement of our financial statements, an executive officer received more compensation than the executive officer would have received absent the incorrect financial
statements. The Board or committee, in its discretion, may then take such actions as it deems necessary or appropriate to address the events that gave rise to the restatement and to prevent its recurrence. Such actions may include, to the extent
permitted by applicable law: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">requiring the executive officer to repay some or all of any bonus or other incentive compensation paid; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">requiring the executive officer to repay any gains realized on the exercise of stock options or on the open-market sale of vested shares; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">canceling some or all of the executive officer&#146;s restricted stock or deferred stock unit grants, performance share units and outstanding stock options; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">adjusting the executive officer&#146;s future compensation; or </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">terminating or initiating legal action against the executive officer. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc119433_38"></A>Trading Restrictions and Anti-Hedging Policy </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our insider trading policy limits the timing and types of transactions in Mondel&#275;z International securities by Section&nbsp;16 officers, including our NEOs (and
any member of the Section&nbsp;16 officer&#146;s family sharing the same household). Among other restrictions, the policy: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">allows Section&nbsp;16 officers to trade company securities only during open window periods and only after they have pre-cleared transactions; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">prohibits Section&nbsp;16 officers from short-selling company securities or &#147;selling against the box&#148; (failing to deliver sold securities); and </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">prohibits Section&nbsp;16 officers from entering into transactions in puts, calls or other derivatives on Mondel&#275;z International securities on an exchange or in any other organized market, as well as any other
derivative or hedging transactions on Mondel&#275;z International securities. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc119433_39"></A>Anti-Pledging Policy
</B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our insider trading policy prohibits our directors, executive officers and certain additional executives from holding Mondel&#275;z International securities in
a margin account or pledging Mondel&#275;z International securities as collateral for a loan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc119433_40"></A>Policy with Respect to
Qualifying Compensation for Tax Deductibility </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Code Section&nbsp;162(m) limits our ability to deduct compensation paid to certain NEOs (the &#147;covered
employees&#148;) to $1.0 million annually. Covered employees under Code Section&nbsp;162(m) include our principal executive officer and our next three highest paid executive officers, other than our principal financial officer. This limitation does
not apply to performance-based compensation, provided certain conditions are satisfied. The Company generally intends that the Annual Cash Incentive Program awards and awards under our equity program qualify as performance-based compensation and are
thus tax-deductible under Code Section&nbsp;162(m). However, the application of Section&nbsp;162(m) is complex and may change with time (with a potentially retroactive effect) and thus there can be no guarantee that all of these awards will actually
qualify as performance-based compensation under Section&nbsp;162(m). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Additionally, the Compensation Committee retains the discretion to authorize payments that may
not be tax-deductible if it believes such payments are in the best interest of shareholders. For example, the Compensation Committee decided, based on benchmarking salaries of other chief executive officers in the Compensation Survey Group, to pay
Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld an annual base salary in excess of $1.0 million. Therefore, a portion of her salary was not tax-deductible in 2015. In addition, a portion of certain of the other covered employees&#146; income exceeded the $1.0 million tax
deductibility limit for 2015 because of other elements of their annual compensation. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;57 </FONT></P>

year as computed in accordance with FASB ASC Topic 718. Assumptions used in the calculation of these amounts are included in Note 11 to the consolidated financial statements contained in our 2015 Form 10-K. For performance share units, the amounts
are based on the probable outcome of the performance conditions as of the grant date. Below is a breakout of the applicable 2015-2017, 2014-2016 and 2013-2015 performance share unit grants for each NEO assuming maximum performance. For

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(a)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Consistent with the findings of an independent, third-party security study, for security and personal safety, we require Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld to use our aircraft for all travel. The incremental cost of personal use of our
aircraft, as reflected in the table, includes the cost of trip-related crew hotels and meals, in-flight food and beverages, landing and ground handling fees, hourly maintenance contract costs, hangar or aircraft parking costs, fuel costs based on
the average annual cost of fuel per hour flown, and other smaller variable costs. Fixed costs that would be incurred in any event to operate our aircraft (for example, aircraft purchase costs, maintenance not related to personal trips and flight
crew salaries) are not included in the incremental cost of Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s use of our aircraft. Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is responsible for taxes in connection with her personal use of our aircraft and we do not reimburse her for those taxes.
</TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(b)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">All executive officers are eligible for an annual financial counseling allowance up to $7,500 and, in the case of Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld, up to $10,000. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(c)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">At the time of his hire in October 2014, Mr.&nbsp;Gladden received our standard executive relocation assistance program, which covers moving, travel, home sale and other expenses in connection with the relocation. Tax
payments are also provided to cover the additional taxes due solely to the relocation assistance program in accordance with the policy. The amounts reflected are residual expenses and related incremental tax payments that were not reported in the
prior year. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(d)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Mr.&nbsp;Cofer, a U.S. expatriate in 2015, received payments in conjunction with his international assignment based in Singapore. These payments to Mr.&nbsp;Cofer were similar to the types of payments generally made to
other employees who accept an international assignment with the Company. The payments are designed to facilitate the relocation of employees to positions in other countries by covering expenses over and above those that employees accepting
assignments would have incurred had they remained in their home countries. These payments include housing expenses, cost of living adjustment, schooling and travel expenses. Similarly, the tax payments are made pursuant to our International
Assignment Policy, which is designed to cover the additional taxes that an employee incurs due solely to the international assignment. The tax equalization amount is negative due to the amount and timing of repayments related to tax equalization
settlements. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Effective January&nbsp;1, 2016, Mr.&nbsp;Clouse is our Executive Vice President and Chief Commercial Officer and Mr.&nbsp;Cofer is our Executive Vice President and Chief Growth Officer. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(7)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Reflects Mr.&nbsp;Marques&#146; one-time cash payment associated with his hire on March&nbsp;9, 2015. The amount is subject to full repayment if his employment terminates before March&nbsp;9, 2017, except upon an
involuntary termination without cause or termination due to death or disability. </TD></TR></TABLE>

performance cycle and will be paid out in cash based on the actual number of shares earned for the performance cycle, if any. The maximum payout equals 200% of target. </TD></TR></TABLE>

financial statements contained in our 2015 Form 10-K. The assumptions for each of the plans are as follows: </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Assumes commencement at the earliest age that participants would be eligible for an unreduced pension benefit, which is age 62, and are <U>discounted</U> for current age; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Measurement date of December&nbsp;31, 2015; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Discount rate of 4.52% (Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Retirement Plan) and 4.49% (Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan I and II); and </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">RP2014 Mortality Table Projected on a Generational Basis with MP2014. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc119433_47"></A>Retirement Benefit Plan Descriptions </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Retirement Plan </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Eligibility for this plan is
limited to employees who were eligible for the Kraft Foods Group, Inc. Retirement Plan prior to our October&nbsp;1, 2012 spin-off of Kraft Foods Group, Inc. As a result, only full-time and part-time U.S. employees hired by Kraft Foods Group, Inc.
before January&nbsp;1, 2009, including our NEOs, are covered automatically in our funded non-contributory, tax-qualified defined benefit plan. Mr.&nbsp;Gladden and Mr.&nbsp;Marques are therefore not eligible for this plan. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Benefits under this plan are payable upon retirement in the form of an annuity or a lump sum (if the employee was hired before 2004). Normal retirement under this plan
is defined as age 65 with five years of vesting service, at which point participants are eligible to receive an unreduced benefit. Vested participants may elect to receive benefits before age 65, but the amount is reduced as benefits are paid over a
longer period of time. Participants must have at least five years of service to become vested. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The formula used to calculate a benefit is equal to the following:
</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">1.3% of final average pay up to the Social Security covered compensation amount multiplied by years of service up to 30; plus </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">1.675% of final average pay in excess of the Social Security covered compensation amount, multiplied by years of service up to 30; plus </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">0.5% of final average pay multiplied by years of service in excess of 30. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Final average pay is defined as the greater
of (a)&nbsp;the average of an executive officer&#146;s salary plus annual bonus during the last 60 consecutive months of service before separation and (b)&nbsp;the five highest consecutive calendar years of salary plus annual bonus out of the last
ten years prior to separation. Social Security covered compensation is an amount equal to the average of the Social Security taxable wage bases for the 35-year period that ends in the year the participant reaches age 65. (If the participant was born
between 1938 and 1954, the 35-year average ends in the year the participant reaches age 66. If the participant was born after 1954, the 35-year average ends in the year the participant reaches age 67.) The Internal Revenue Service has established
certain limits on how much employees may receive from this plan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is eligible to retire under the Mondel&#275;z
Global LLC Retirement Plan. Employees hired before January&nbsp;1, 2004 with at least ten years of service are eligible to retire under this plan at age 55. The benefits payable to employees eligible to retire before age 62 are reduced by 3% each
year (maximum 20%) between age 62 and the year that the employee retires. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan I </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Code limits the amount employees may receive from the tax-qualified pension plan. Therefore, we offer a supplemental defined benefit pension program under the
Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan I. Only employees who are participants in our tax-qualified pension plan participate in this unfunded program. As a result, </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;64 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
neither Mr.&nbsp;Gladden nor Mr.&nbsp;Marques are eligible to receive a non-qualified supplemental defined pension benefit under this program. This non-qualified program provides for the
difference between what would have been payable based upon the pension plan formula stated above absent the applicable Code limits and the amount actually payable from the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Retirement Plan. Additionally, any eligible base
salary and annual cash incentive deferrals made under the voluntary non-qualified deferred compensation plan are considered non-qualified earnings and are subsequently paid out under this program regardless of whether or not the executive exceeds
the applicable Code limits. Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is eligible to retire under the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan I. Employees hired before January&nbsp;1, 2004 with at least ten years of service are eligible to retire under this
plan at age 55. The benefits payable to employees eligible to retire before age 62 are reduced by 3% each year (maximum 20%) between age 62 and the year that the employee retires. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan II &#150; Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s employment offer letter provided her with credited service during the period she was not working for the Company between 2004 and 2006. This
enhanced pension benefit was part of a broader incentive program designed to compensate Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld for the forfeiture of benefits at her prior employer, as well as to encourage her to return to the Company. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is eligible to retire with unreduced benefits under the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan II. </P>

<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf" ALIGN="right">&#150;</TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(5)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Reflects the number of vested performance-contingent restricted stock units granted to Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld on December&nbsp;19, 2012. Pursuant to the terms of the grant, as of December&nbsp;19, 2014, Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld
vested in her performance-contingent restricted stock units; however, shares were not distributed until December&nbsp;19, 2015. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondel&#275;z
Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan I </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Because the Code limits the amount that may be contributed to the tax-qualified defined contribution plan on behalf of
an employee, we offer a supplemental defined contribution program under the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan I. This is an unfunded program that allows eligible employees to defer a portion of their annual compensation (base
salary and AIP awards) and receive corresponding matching amounts to the extent that their contributions to the tax-qualified defined contribution plan (and the corresponding matching contributions) are limited by Code Section&nbsp;401(a)(17).
Executives must defer receipt of the payments until retirement. Executive contributions and employer matching amounts earn the same rate of return as the Income Fund, which is a market rate fund available to employees in the tax-qualified defined
contribution plan. The rate of return under this investment fund in 2015 was 1.97%. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Executive Deferred Compensation Plan </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The MEDCP is a non-qualified plan that allows our NEOs to defer, on a pre-tax basis, up to 50% of salary and up to 100% of their AIP award. The investment choices are
similar to those offered to eligible employees in our U.S. 401(k) plan. Participants may elect to defer their compensation until they separate from service as determined under Code Section&nbsp;409A. They may also elect to receive distributions of
their accounts while still employed with the Company, but the plan requires a minimum deferral period of two years. Distributions may be made in a lump sum or in annual installments of between two and ten years. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The investment alternatives available to the executives under the MEDCP are selected by the Company and may be changed from time to time. Participants are permitted to
change their investment elections at any time on a prospective basis. The table below shows the available funds under the MEDCP and their annual rate of return for the calendar year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. </P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc119433_49"></A>Potential Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The narrative and tables below describe the potential payments to each NEO upon certain terminations, including following a change in control. In accordance with SEC
rules, all information described in this section is presented as if the triggering events occurred on December&nbsp;31, 2015. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Involuntary Termination Without
Cause (Non-Change in Control Event) </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We generally do not have existing employment or separation agreements with our NEOs that dictate the terms of the NEO&#146;s
departure from the Company. However, in the event an NEO is involuntarily terminated without cause outside </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;66 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
of a change in control event, we would expect that in most cases our Compensation Committee would offer separation benefits as consideration for protections we would likely seek &#150; such as a
release of claims and entering into non-compete, non-solicitation and confidentiality agreements. For our U.S. salaried employees, we maintain a severance plan that provides severance pay of up to 12 months based on service where the employee&#146;s
job is eliminated. We would expect to treat our NEOs at least comparably to other U.S. salaried employees who are involuntarily terminated without cause. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The
following chart reflects the typical separation benefits that may be offered to an NEO who is involuntarily terminated without cause. Actual terms and conditions would be determined by our Compensation Committee based on the particular facts in a
specific case. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Treatment of AIP Award</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Prorated AIP award based on actual business performance results and target individual
performance.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Treatment of PSU Grants</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Outstanding PSU grants are generally forfeited, however our Compensation Committee may
exercise discretion to vest awards subject to actual Company performance.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Treatment of Other Equity Grants</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Restricted stock, deferred stock unit and unvested stock option grants are generally
forfeited, however our Compensation Committee may exercise discretion to accelerate vesting.</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Potential Payout Upon an Involuntary Termination Without Cause at Fiscal Year-End 2015 </B></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Change in Control Arrangements </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">NEOs are not eligible for any benefit solely upon a change in control. We maintain the CIC Plan for senior executive officers, including the NEOs, which provides for
certain benefits upon an involuntary termination of employment without &#147;Cause&#148; or voluntary termination for &#147;Good Reason&#148; within two years following a change in control. To receive any benefits under the CIC Plan, all
participants must execute and abide by certain restrictive covenants, including a non-compete and non-solicitation for one year following termination. Additionally, the Mondel&#275;z International, Inc. Amended and Restated 2005 Performance
Incentive Plan (the &#147;Equity Plan&#148;) also provides for the treatment of unassumed outstanding equity grants following a change in control and assumed outstanding equity grants upon an involuntary termination of employment without
&#147;Cause&#148; or voluntary termination for &#147;Good Reason&#148; within two years following a change in control. The key elements of the CIC Plan and Equity Plan assuming a &#147;double trigger&#148; event are described in the table below.
</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="18%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="80%"></TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#4c4c4c" STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Plan Element</FONT></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Description</FONT></B></FONT></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Definition of Change</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">in Control (&#147;CIC&#148;)</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Subject to certain exceptions, the occurrence of one of the
conditions below:</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Acquisition of 20% or more of our outstanding voting
securities;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Changes to Board membership during any consecutive
24-month period that results in less than 50% of the current Board members elected to the Board;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our merger or consolidation with another company,
and</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:4.00em; text-indent:-2.00em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;we are not the surviving
company; or</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:4.00em; text-indent:-2.00em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;the other entity
owns 50% or more of our outstanding voting securities; or</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Complete liquidation of Mondel&#275;z International
or the sale of all or substantially all of our assets.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Definition of &#147;Cause&#148;</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Continued failure to substantially perform the
participant&#146;s job duties (other than resulting from incapacity due to disability);</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gross negligence, dishonesty or violation of any
reasonable rule or regulation of the Company where the violation results in significant damage to the Company; or</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Engaging in other conduct which adversely reflects
on Company in any material respect.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Definition of &#147;Good Reason&#148;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Material reduction in job duties;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Material reduction in compensation; or</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Relocation beyond 50 miles.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Severance and Benefits Amounts</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;CEO: 2.99 times base salary plus target annual
incentive;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;All other NEOs: two times base salary plus target
annual incentive;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Additional credited years of pension service (if
applicable) and welfare benefits equal to three years for the CEO and two years for the other NEOs;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Continuation of financial counseling and car
allowances for three years for the CEO and two years for the other NEOs; and</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Outplacement services up to two years following the
CIC.</P></TD></TR>

AIP and the NEO&#146;s outstanding PSU grants paid at target levels, each on a pro rata basis for service during the performance cycle, except where at least fifty percent of the performance cycle has elapsed for outstanding PSUs resulting in a cash
payment equal to the target level.</P></TD></TR>

<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(6)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The amounts reflect the value for continuation of the financial counseling allowance (three years for Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld valued at $30,000 and two years for all other NEOs valued at $15,000), car allowance (three years
for Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld valued at $69,999 and two years for all other NEOs valued at $30,000) and outplacement services (two years for all NEOs valued at $25,000). </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(7)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The amount reflects an additional three years of pension accrual for Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld and two years of pension accrual for all other eligible NEOs. Mr.&nbsp;Gladden and Mr.&nbsp;Marques are not pension eligible.
</TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Potential Payout Upon Other Types of Separations </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In the
event an NEO terminates employment due to death or disability, all outstanding unvested restricted stock, deferred stock units and stock option grants would vest in all cases. In addition, the NEO (or beneficiary) would become eligible for prorated
awards under the AIP and outstanding PSUs assuming the termination event occurs in the 2<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">nd</SUP> or 3<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">rd</SUP> year of the performance cycle. </P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The amounts reflect the value of the vesting of all outstanding unvested restricted stock, deferred stock units and stock options as of the effective date of termination, based on a December&nbsp;31, 2015 closing stock
price of $44.84. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In the event an NEO terminates employment due to normal retirement (retirement on or after age 65 with five years of service), all
outstanding unvested restricted stock, deferred stock units and stock option grants would vest. The NEO would also be eligible for a prorated award under the AIP, but any outstanding PSUs would vest at the discretion of the Compensation Committee.
None of our NEOs is eligible for normal retirement on December&nbsp;31, 2015. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;69 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In the event an NEO separates due to early retirement (retirement on or after age 55, but before age 65, and with at least
ten years of service), he or she could be considered for partial awards under the AIP and equity program, at the discretion of our Compensation Committee. The value of the total payments for each NEO could range from zero to an amount generally no
greater than the amounts shown above for termination due to death or disability. Beginning with 2016 equity grants, for all separations due to retirement (retirement on or after age 55 with at least ten years of service) all unvested deferred stock
units and PSUs, excluding stock options, will pro rata vest, subject to actual Company performance, based on the number of months employed during the vesting period or participating during the performance cycle, as applicable. Unvested stock options
will continue to vest per the original vesting schedule, provided the employee is actively employed for three months following the grant date. </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:24pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P><div style="width:100%;margin-left:0%; margin-right:0%;background-color:#eaeaea;padding-top:2pt;padding-bottom:3pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; padding-top:0pt; margin-left:2%; font-size:16pt; font-family:ARIAL"><A NAME="toc119433_50"></A>Human Resources and Compensation Committee Report for the Year Ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2%; margin-right:2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Compensation Committee oversees our compensation programs on behalf of the Board. In fulfilling its oversight responsibilities, the
Compensation Committee reviewed and discussed with management the Compensation Discussion and Analysis included in this Proxy Statement. Based on that review and discussion, the Compensation Committee recommended that the Board include the
Compensation Discussion and Analysis in our Proxy Statement to be filed with the SEC in connection with our Annual Meeting and incorporate it by reference in our Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, filed with the
SEC on February&nbsp;19, 2016. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Human Resources and Compensation Committee: </B></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:16pt; font-family:ARIAL"><A NAME="toc119433_51"></A>Ownership of Equity Securities </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows the number of shares of our Common Stock beneficially owned as of March&nbsp;9, 2016, unless otherwise noted, by each director and NEO, as
well as the number of shares beneficially owned by all of our current directors and executive officers as a group. None of our Common Stock owned by these individuals is subject to any pledge. Unless otherwise indicated, each of the named
individuals has sole voting and investment power with respect to the shares shown. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
